#week-title("One", "Opening the Year Two Letter")

=== Core Teaching

At the close of Year Two, the student sealed a letter to their future self —
an honest account of where they stood at the threshold of the Adept tier,
what they expected of Year Three, what they feared, and what they intended.
That letter is now opened.

The Year Two letter was written with less experience and more anticipation than
the Year One letter. The practitioner writing at the end of Year Two had
completed two years of genuine work, had crossed into the mineral kingdom
philosophically, had sealed a long circulation, had made the Adept's Covenant.
They had clear ambitions for Year Three and probably some accurate intuitions
about what it would demand.

Reading it now, at the end of Year Three, is a different experience from
reading the Year One letter at the end of Year Two. The distance between the
Year Two self and the present self is shorter in calendar time but possibly
deeper in terms of what the Work has done. Year Three's mineral work, extended
vigil, full constitutional review, and engagement with Canseliet's standard
have operated on a different level from Year One's foundational work.

*What to attend to in the reading:*
- What did the Year Two self predict accurately about Year Three?
- What was completely unexpected?
- What fear proved groundless? What fear proved justified?
- What intention from Year Two has been fulfilled? What remains unfulfilled —
  and is the remaining intention still meaningful, or has the Work revealed
  it as a projection?
- What did the Year Two self understand about the Work that the present self
  has, in some respects, complicated or moved beyond?

After reading, write a reply to the Year Two self. One paragraph. Speak honestly
to the practitioner who was about to begin Year Three.

=== Topics This Week

- Opening and reading the Year Two sealed letter
- Attending to: predictions, surprises, fears, intentions
- Writing the reply to the Year Two self
- What three years of correspondence with the self reveals

#inner-work[
  *The Year Two Reply*

  After reading the Year Two letter, write the reply. What does the practitioner
  who has completed Year Three say to the one who was about to begin it?

  Keep the reply to one paragraph. The most useful reply is the one that speaks
  most directly and most honestly — not the most eloquent.
